
Your timer **doesn’t stop** because `return` only exits the callback function – **it does NOT stop `setInterval`**.

To stop an interval, you must call **`clearInterval(intervalId)`**.

***

## ✅ Correct Way to Stop `setInterval`

### ✅ FIXED CODE

```js
let timer = 0;

const intervalId = setInterval(() => {
  if (timer === 6) {
    clearInterval(intervalId); // ✅ stops the timer
  } else {
    console.log(timer);
    timer++;
  }
}, 1000);
```

***

## ✅ Output

    0
    1
    2
    3
    4
    5

✅ Stops automatically at `6`.

***

## ❌ Why Your Code Didn’t Work

```js
if (timer === 6) {
  return;   // ❌ Only exits this function call
}
```

### Important concept:

> **`return` does NOT clear an interval**  
> It only exits the current callback execution.

The browser will still call the function again after 1 second.

***

## ✅ How `setInterval` Works (Mental Model)

```text
setInterval → returns an ID
              ↓
           intervalId
              ↓
      clearInterval(intervalId)
```

Without the ID, JavaScript **cannot stop the interval**.

***

## ✅ Alternative: Stop after printing 6 (Cleaner Version)

```js
let timer = 0;

const id = setInterval(() => {
  console.log(timer);
  timer++;

  if (timer > 5) {
    clearInterval(id);
  }
}, 1000);
```

✅ Often preferred in interviews.

***

## ✅ Countdown Version (Bonus)

```js
let timer = 6;

const id = setInterval(() => {
  console.log(timer);

  if (timer === 0) {
    clearInterval(id);
  }

  timer--;
}, 1000);
```

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Explanation ⭐

> **`setInterval` runs repeatedly until it is explicitly stopped using `clearInterval`. Returning from the callback does not stop the interval; you must store the interval ID and clear it.**

***

## ✅ Key Takeaways

✔ `setInterval()` always returns an ID  
✔ `return` does NOT stop the timer  
✔ `clearInterval(id)` stops it  
✔ Always store interval ID in a variable

